example.p:
To solve 2(x-3)+5\,=\,9, we replace it with a sequence of equivalent equations.

		2(x-3)+5\,\amp=\,9
		2(x-3)+5\,{\color{blue}-5}\,\amp=\,9\,{\color{blue}-5}
		2(x-3)\,\amp=\,4
		2(x-3)\,{\color{blue}\div 2}\,\amp=\,4 \,{\color{blue}{\div 2}}
		x-3 \,\amp=\, 2
		x-3 \,{\color{blue}+3}\,\amp=\, 2 \,{\color{blue}+3}
		x \,\amp=\, 5

		showing that x=5 is the unique solution to the original equation.

solution.p:
3 \leq 4x + 2 \lt 8 1 \leq 4x \lt 6 \frac{1}{4} \leq x \lt \frac{6}{4} \frac{1}{4} \leq x \lt \frac{3}{2}
This says 1/4 \leq x AND x \lt 3/2. Plotting each interval we see
To be in both intervals, x must be in their intersection (See .) So the solution set is \left[\frac{1}{4},+\infty\right) \cap \left(-\infty,\frac{3}{2}\right) = \left[\frac{1}{4},\frac{3}{2}\right).

example.p:
To solve 4x^2 - 9 = 0, we first note that there is no degree one term. So

				4x^2 - 9 &= 0
				4x^2  &= 9
				x^2  &= \frac{9}{4}
				x  &= \pm \sqrt{\frac{9}{4}} = \pm \frac{\sqrt{9}}{\sqrt{4}}= \pm \frac{3}{2}

			That is, x=3/2 OR x=-3/2.

solution.p:
Isolate the squared expression (x-1)^2 first
3(x-1)^2 - 6 &= 0 3(x-1)^2 &= 6 (x-1)^2 &= \frac{6}{3} = 2 x-1 &= \pm \sqrt{2} x &= 1 \pm \sqrt{2}
Estimating with a calculator, x = 1 + \sqrt{2} \approx 2.414 OR x=1-\sqrt{2} \approx -0.414.
